      People are no longer=C2=A0worried about bond market liquidity
   =20
 =20

Well,  here you go:

Liquidity is no longer the biggest worry for traders in financial markets, =
following a year in which markets survived a series of major shocks without=
 the ability to buy and sell becoming too severely impaired.
Instead, volatility has climbed to the top of the list of traders=E2=80=99 =
concerns in 2023, as rising global interest rates and geopolitical tensions=
 spark big moves in markets, according to a survey of traders by JPMorgan.
Traders and investors had for the previous six years listed liquidity as th=
eir biggest concern, with many worrying about the risk of a financial accid=
ent caused by a breakdown in the functioning of important markets, includin=
g in US Treasuries that form the bedrock of global finance.
But Scott Wacker, head of fixed income, currency and commodity ecommerce sa=
les at JPMorgan said that in 2022 =E2=80=9Cwe didn=E2=80=99t see many break=
s in the system in terms of liquidity=E2=80=9D, despite market shocks inclu=
ding the fallout from Russia=E2=80=99s invasion of Ukraine and the crisis t=
hat hit UK pension funds and the gilt market.
=E2=80=9CThe underlying availability of liquidity was there and the markets=
 functioned really well,=E2=80=9D he said.

You could have a model that is like =E2=80=9Cwhen markets are calm and noth=
ing is happening, people worry that if things=C2=A0do happen they won=E2=80=
=99t be able to sell their stuff, but when things are happening regularly, =
people are more worried about the things that are happening than they are a=
bout their hypothetical ability to sell stuff.=E2=80=9D When liquidity is g=
ood and there are no crises, it is easy to say =E2=80=94=C2=A0and hard to d=
isprove =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwell if there=C2=A0was=C2=A0a crisis, liqui=
dity would be bad.=E2=80=9D But once you have enough crises and liquidity k=
eeps being fine, you have to stop saying that.
Also, I mean, one could quibble. Russia invaded Ukraine and, as an indirect=
 result, the London Metal=C2=A0Exchange=C2=A0shut down nickel trading for a=
 week. Not very good liquidity, in nickel, that week. But when you=E2=80=99=
re surveyed at the end of the year, you might not remember that as a=C2=A0l=
iquidity problem; you might remember that as an extreme instance of market =
volatility. =E2=80=9CLiquidity=E2=80=9D is sort of an abstract structural=
=C2=A0thing to worry about when you don=E2=80=99t have any immediate worrie=
s; when you have the immediate worries, you tend not to think of them as =
=E2=80=9Cliquidity.=E2=80=9D

