om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  t=
imes</a> recently about the cleverness of AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=
=E2=80=99s APE stock issuance plan, but I am ashamed to admit that I missed=
 the cleverest part. I now propose to=C2=A0fix that.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The situation with the APEs is this. In the la=
st couple of years, AMC has sold a ton of stock, largely at meme-driven hig=
h prices, and has used the money=C2=A0for corporate finance purposes like <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjgva25vd2=
luZy13aGVuLXRvLXNlbGwtZ2FtZXN0b3Atc3RvY2stYXQtdGhlLXRvcC1pcy1pbXBvc3NpYmxlP=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
ZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBb8b1faee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  avoiding bankruptcy</a> and, uh, getti=
ng into <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.2=
66450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtM=
TUvYW1jLWJvdWdodC1hLWdvbGQtbWluZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1f=
bWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMDEmdXRtX2N=
hbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2ddd69f4" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  gold =
mining</a>. It would like to sell more stock, but it has a problem. Under i=
ts <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwND=
Y1OTEzMDkyMDAxL2ExMy0yNjk1N18xZXgzZDEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8809dd1=
4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> corporate charter</a>, it only has 524,173,073 authorized com=
mon shares, and has issued more or less all of them. (There are <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIzMDA3NTUw=
L3RtMjMyNzAwLTFfcHJlMTRhLmh0bSN0U09PQw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2eae9461" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> 517,580,416 shares outstanding</a> at last count.)=C2=A0It still ne=
eds money, but it has no more shares to sell.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The charter can be amended to authorize more s=
hares, and AMC tried. But to amend the charter, AMC would=C2=A0need the app=
roval of=C2=A0a majority of its shareholders, and it apparently couldn=E2=
=80=99t get that approval.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> Part of the problem seems to be that AMC=E2=80=99s largely retail inve=
stor base didn=E2=80=99t want it to issue more shares, because they do not =
like dilution. But another =E2=80=94=C2=A0I suspect, bigger =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
part of the problem is that much of AMC=E2=80=99s largely retail investor b=
ase=C2=A0<em>doesn=E2=80=99t vote at all</em>. <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjQvYW1jLXMtYXBlcy1taWdodC1zdGljay1hc=
m91bmQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291=
cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf5ecc1e8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Retail investors</a> famously <a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0=
cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDktMDEvdGhlLXR=
ydW1wLXNwYWMtbmVlZHMtbW9yZS10aW1lP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV=
9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIwMSZ1dG1fY=
2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc49a83b2" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  don=
=E2=80=99t vote</a>, because it is inconvenient, because they don=E2=80=99t=
 get clear communications about votes from their brokers, because it is not=
 individually rational to vote a small number of shares, etc. At AMC=E2=80=
=99s annual meeting in 2022, only <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2h=
pdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wMDAxNTU4MzcwMjIwMTAxMDAvYW1jLTIwMjIwNjE2eD=
hrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB39354914" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> about 145 million</a> =
of its 517 million outstanding shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0or 28% =E2=80=94 voted=
 for=C2=A0<em>or</em> against its director nominees (mostly for); the rest =
just didn=E2=80=99t vote.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For directors, that=E2=80=99s fine; directors =
just need a majority=C2=A0of the shares that actually vote, so getting 75% =
yes votes from the 28% of shares that bothered voting is enough. But for a =
charter amendment, it=E2=80=99s not: The amendment requires majority approv=
al from=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>the shares, so=C2=A0<em>not voting</em> has =
the=C2=A0same effect=C2=A0as <em>voting against=C2=A0</em>the amendment. If=
 24% of the shares voted in favor and 4% voted against, that=E2=80=99s stil=
l a loss; you need more than 50%=C2=A0of=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em>of the shar=
es.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC couldn=E2=80=99t issue more common shares.=
 So it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.26=
6450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMj=
MvYW1jLWdvZXMtYXBlP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMDEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1ha=
WwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDIwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9u=
ZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb113745b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  invented APEs</a>. =
APEs are a new class of AMC share, technically called AMC Preferred Equity =
Units. APEs are preferred stock, not common stock, so they are not subject =
to the charter=E2=80=99s cap of 524,173,073 authorized shares. And AMC=E2=
=80=99s charter =E2=80=94=C2=A0like the charters of many US public companie=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0contains a =E2=80=9Cblank check=E2=80=9D preferred stock p=
rovision, saying that the board can issue preferred stock with whatever ter=
ms it likes, without shareholder approval.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So AMC=E2=80=99s board used that provision to=
=C2=A0issue=C2=A0APEs=C2=A0with terms identical to those of the common stoc=
k. APEs get the same economic rights (dividend, payments in liquidation, et=
c.) as the common stock; they also get the same voting rights. On anything =
that requires a shareholder vote, the common shares and APE units vote toge=
ther, and each gets one vote. Also, the APEs will automatically=C2=A0<em>co=
nvert=C2=A0</em>into common stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0one APE will become=C2=A0o=
ne share of common stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0if and when AMC gets shareholder ap=
proval to issue enough stock to cover all the APEs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A technical digression. AMC=E2=80=99s charter =
allows it to issue preferred stock with any terms it wants, but the charter=
 does have a cap on the=C2=A0<em>number=C2=A0</em>of preferred shares. That=
 cap is 50 million preferred shares (separate from the cap of=C2=A0524,173,=
073 common shares). AMC wanted to issue a lot more than 50 million=C2=A0APE=
s, but fortunately there is an easy=C2=A0solution. Remember, the preferred =
stock can have any terms that AMC=E2=80=99s board wants, so AMC made each p=
referred share equivalent (in voting and economic rights) to <em>100</em> c=
ommon shares, and then it made each APE =E2=80=94=C2=A0technically not a sh=
are at all, but an AMC Preferred Equity <em>unit=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0e=
qual to 1/100th of a preferred share. If you buy an APE unit, what you are =
getting is 1/100th of an AMC preferred share, which is equivalent to 100 co=
mmon shares, so you are getting the equivalent of one common share. It all =
works out. And AMC=E2=80=99s board authorized one billion APEs, which would=
 take only 10 million of the 50 million preferred shares it is allowed to i=
ssue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Nobody really wants to issue=C2=A01/100ths of =
a share, though, so AMC is not actually issuing fractional preferred shares=
. Mechanically what happens is that when AMC issues APEs, it actually issue=
s (whole shares of) preferred stock to a=C2=A0<em>depositary</em>, a bank o=
r trust company that holds onto the shares for it, and the depositary issue=
s APE units. AMC=E2=80=99s depositary is Computershare Trust Co., which doe=
s a lot of this sort of business.=C2=A0What you have bought, when you buy a=
n APE, is a depositary receipt from Computershare representing 1/100th of a=
n AMC preferred share. And Computershare actually owns the preferred shares=
, on behalf of all the APE unit holders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess this all sounds weird and convoluted, =
but it=E2=80=99s actually a pretty common mechanism. Companies that issue a=
 lot of retail-oriented fixed-income preferred stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0banks, =
for instance =E2=80=94=C2=A0often use depositary receipts, so that each pre=
ferred <em>share</em> has a face value of, like, $25,000, but the units tha=
t trade=C2=A0on exchanges are like 1/1,000th of a preferred share with a fa=
ce value of $25.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgro=
und-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a> So here is a 2022=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.=
