<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Okay, digression over! AMC issued the APEs, wh=
ich are meant to be economically equivalent to common stock. It <a href=3D"=
https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d=
3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMDkyMzk3=
L3RtMjIyMzc4MGQxX2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB44a3932d" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 started last August</a> by doing a sort of stock split: It paid a dividend=
 of one APE per common share, so that if you previously owned 25 common sha=
res now you owned 25 common shares and 25 APEs. And then =E2=80=94=C2=A0bec=
ause it could not sell any more common shares, but=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em=
>sell APEs =E2=80=94=C2=A0it started selling more APEs for cash. In Septemb=
er, it registered to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0=
MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIyMTAyODMzL3RtMjIyNjM1MC0xXzQyNGI1Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB88ca2b3e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> sell up to 425 million</a> of them in publi=
c at-the-market offerings, and started <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0=
FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMTQxMTU3OS8wMDAxNDExNTc5MjIwMDAwODIvYW1jLTIwMjIwO=
TMweDEwcS5odG0jTk9URVNUT0NPTlNPTElEQVRFREZJTkFOQ0lBTFNUQVRFTUVOVFNfOQ/607f0=
7ceef4b8524a319a23cB55c50c6a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope=
" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> selling steadily</a>; in December it=
=C2=A0sold about 257.6 million APEs to a hedge fund called Antara Capital.<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0There are now about <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9=
kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIzMDA3NTUwL3RtMjMyNzAwLTFfcHJlMTRhLmh0bSN0U0=
9PQw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC2eae9461" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> 929.8 million APEs outstan=
ding</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">AMC hoped, I suppose, that people would treat =
the APEs and common shares as equivalent, and that they=E2=80=99d trade at =
similar prices, but that didn=E2=80=99t really happen. By the end of 2022, =
AMC common shares were at $4.07, while APEs were at $1.41. This is untidy a=
nd annoying =E2=80=94=C2=A0similar things should trade at similar prices =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but it is also bad for AMC as a corporate finance matter, be=
cause it is going around selling stuff that is equivalent to common stock a=
t a 65% discount to its common stock price.=C2=A0<em>That=C2=A0</em>is dilu=
tive.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So AMC is once again going to its shareholders=
 to ask them to vote to approve a charter amendment to authorize more share=
s, so that it can=C2=A0convert<em> </em>the APEs into common stock and then=
 go sell more common stock. Here is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlc=
y9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIzMDA3NTUwL3RtMjMyNzAwLTFfcHJlMTRh=
Lmh0bSN0UE4x/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2b6a4301" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> proposed amendment=
</a> to authorize more shares, and here is a=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIzMDA3NTUwL3RtMjMyNzAwLT=
FfcHJlMTRhLmh0bSN0UE4y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6dad4a2e" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">related a=
mendment</a> to do a 1-for-10 reverse stock split, where 10 old AMC common =
shares (or APEs) will convert into one new share. If these amendments pass,=
 AMC will have 550 million authorized common shares (up slightly=C2=A0from =
the current 524 million), but, because of the reverse split, it will only h=
ave about 145 million outstanding (roughly 52 million from the old common s=
hares and roughly 93 million from the conversion of the APEs). So it will h=
ave lots more room to issue lots more shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course, AMC tried to get this vote before, =
and couldn=E2=80=99t. But as I have said before,=C2=A0the APEs should impro=
ve AMC=E2=80=99s ability to get the vote:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The APEs get to vote along with the c=
ommon stock: AMC just needs a majority of all of the combined votes, APEs p=
lus common.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is very much in an =
APE holder=E2=80=99s self-interest to vote in favor of the amendment, since=
 that will cause an APE (which closed yesterday at $2.42) to convert into a=
 common share ($5.35), which is better. If you own an APE, you probably wan=
t the amendment to pass, so you will pay attention to this vote and vote in=
 favor, even if that requires modest effort and mild inconvenience.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You would expect that the APEs would have=
 migrated=C2=A0away from retail investors (who seem not to like them) into =
the hands of professional arbitrageurs=C2=A0(who are betting on convergence=
 between APEs and common shares), and those arbitrageurs are more likely to=
 vote.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There are just=C2=A0<em>mor=
e=C2=A0</em>APEs than common shares, because AMC keeps selling APEs. At las=
t count there were about 517.6 million common shares outstanding, versus ab=
out 929.8 million APEs.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A big bloc=
k of those APEs=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0some 257.6 million =E2=80=94=C2=A0were =
placed with Antara, which signed an agreement with AMC in which it (1) prom=
ised to hold its APEs=C2=A0through the shareholder vote and (2) promised to=
 vote in favor of the amendment.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">None of that is a guarantee, though. But I mis=
sed the best and cleverest part. In my defense, it was in section 4.5 of th=
e <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/=
aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MTE1NzkvMDAwMTEwNDY=
1OTIyMDg2MTQ0L3RtMjIyMjQyMmQzX2V4NC0xLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc34089=
0a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> deposit agreement</a> governing the APEs, not the most obviou=
s place to look. Section 4.5 says that, if AMC holds a shareholder vote, th=
e depositary for the APEs will pass along voting materials to APE holders, =
and will vote based on their instructions. Standard stuff. But it ends with=
 this sentence<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the absence of specific instruc=
tions from Holders of Receipts, the Depositary will vote the Preferred Stoc=
k represented by the AMC Preferred Equity Units evidenced by the Receipts o=
f such Holders proportionately with votes cast pursuant to instructions rec=
eived from the other Holders.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Get it? AMC doesn=E2=80=99t really need to get=
 votes from the APEs, which are after all not technically shares. It needs =
to get votes from the=C2=A0<em>preferred stock</em>, 100% of which is held =
by Computershare. And, when the APEs were set up,=C2=A0Computershare agreed=
 that it would vote all of its preferred shares,=C2=A0<em>even if some APE =
holders didn=E2=80=99t vote</em>. If holders of 300 million APEs vote yes, =
and holders of 75 million APEs vote no, and the remaining 554 million APEs =
don=E2=80=99t vote at all,=C2=A0then Computershare will vote 80% of its pre=
ferred stock (743.8 million votes) yes and 20% (186 million votes) no, with=
 no abstentions. And that will be enough for the amendment to pass.<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice, anyone who bothers to vote their =
APEs is probably going to vote in favor of the amendment =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
 amendment is clearly good for the APEs, and Antara has committed to voting=
 for it =E2=80=94 so Computershare will probably end up voting close to 100=
% of the preferred stock for the amendment, which is more than enough for i=
t to pass.=C2=A0So the proposal will probably pass. AMC has=C2=A0<em>solved=
=C2=A0</em>the problem of retail non-voting, by giving its retail sharehold=
ers=C2=A0APE units that (1) have voting rights but (2) don=E2=80=99t rely o=
n most of the holders=C2=A0<em>actually bothering to vote</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know!=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s so goo=
d! You can complain! It is all a little aggressive, and in=C2=A0a sense it =
defeats the spirit of the requirement that a majority of shareholders shoul=
d have to vote to amend the corporate charter.<a class=3D"footnote-index" h=
ref=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importa=
nt; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-s=
tyle: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: i=
nline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But, you know, it=E2=80=99s AMC, man. This is a company that has =
embraced being a meme stock, that says it is=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly9naXptb2RvLmNvbS9=
hbWMtYmVsb25ncy10by10aGUtcGVvcGxlLW5vdy0xODQ3MDIxODI3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB13ab1a96" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">80% owned</a> by retail investors, that <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdX=
QtdGhlLXBvcGNvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpb=
CZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25l=
eXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4247c4e9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  gives them popcorn</a=
>; it is on the cutting edge of innovation in=C2=A0retail investor relation=
s and retail corporate governance.=C2=A0When AMC proposed the APEs, back in=
 August, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.=
266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgt=
MjQvYW1jLXMtYXBlcy1taWdodC1zdGljay1hcm91bmQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwMTIzX01PTkVZU1R=
VRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMj=
AxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCf5ecc1e8" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  I wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The meme-stock era has revolutionized corporat=
e governance and investor relations in various strange ways. Now if you are=
 a meme-stock company, or if you want to become one, you have to think abou=
t how to appeal to and connect with retail investors; this means embracing =
memes and taking retail investors=E2=80=99 questions on earnings calls and =
handing out free popcorn with shares and, crucially, using at-the-market of=
ferings to sell stock directly to retail investors rather than relying on i=
nstitutions. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still there are some kinks to work out, and vo=
ting is a big one. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0If you are a meme-stock company with a re=
tail-focused investor-relations function, you have to solve the problem of =
voting. Though I assume that if anyone can do it,=C2=A0AMC can.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It did!</p>
