<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Active ESG</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a few times recently about <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cH=
M6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQyOTY0OTc/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB77d5e4ce" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a paper</a> finding that manager=
s of environmental, social and governance-oriented mutual funds who have mo=
re of their own money in their funds tend to have worse ESG performance: Th=
eir funds invest in companies that get worse ESG scores from public ESG rat=
ers. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.2664=
50/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjMv=
ZXZlcnl0aGluZy1pcy1hbHNvLWJhbmstZnJhdWQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkY=
mdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjAxJn=
V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3be3107f" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 One possible interpretation</a> of this is that ESG managers don=E2=80=99t=
 really =E2=80=9Cbelieve in=E2=80=9D ESG: If their own money is on the line=
, they tend to prioritize financial performance over ESG, and they don=E2=
=80=99t think that ESG really contributes to financial performance, so they=
 pick companies with worse ESG scores.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMzAvaWJ1eWVycy1ib3VnaHQtaGlnaC1hbmQtc29sZC1sb3c_Y21=
waWQ9QkJEMDIwMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3=
NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMjAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b=
8524a319a23cB73df1877" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targe=
t=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bor=
der-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: s=
olid; background-color: #ccc;"> another possible interpretation</a> is that=
 ESG scores are not a great measure of ESG-ness: Managers who don=E2=80=99t=
 care deeply about ESG (1) don=E2=80=99t put their own money in their funds=
=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>(2) blindly track published ESG scores, while manag=
ers who=C2=A0<em>do=C2=A0</em>care deeply invest their own money and make t=
heir own, nuanced, personal ESG judgments that do not necessarily align wit=
h published scores.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, here is a recent paper on =E2=80=9C=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aH=
R0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN0X2lkPTQzMzU2O=
Dg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCc7f1ae73" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">The Complex Materiality of ES=
G Ratings: Evidence from Actively Managed ESG Funds</a>,=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0M=
artijn Cremers, Timothy B. Riley and=C2=A0Rafael Zambrana, arguing that the=
re is more to ESG than published ratings:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We introduce Active ESG Share as a=
 novel metric of the extent of a fund manager=E2=80=99s use of ESG informat=
ion. Active ESG Share compares the full distribution of a portfolio=E2=80=
=99s stock-level ESG ratings to that of its benchmark, capturing how active=
ly a manager uses ESG information, rather than whether the manager tends to=
 favor stocks with high or low ESG ratings. We find a positive relation bet=
ween Active ESG Share and the future performance of actively managed mutual=
 funds, but only among ESG funds, which we attribute to the importance of s=
pecialization. The results are strongest for ESG funds that tend to hold st=
ocks with a high level of ESG ratings disagreement or uncertainty, consiste=
nt with such disagreement and uncertainty creating opportunity for active m=
anagers. Our results suggest that ESG information is financially material, =
but complex, and thus cannot be successfully capitalized on using simple di=
rectional strategies.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They write:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We measure the influence of ESG information on=
 portfolio construction through a novel metric we label =E2=80=98Active ESG=
 Share.=E2=80=99 We calculate Active ESG Share by comparing the portfolio w=
eights of a fund to those in its benchmark at the ESG ratings level. Conseq=
uently, a higher Active ESG Share indicates that the ESG ratings distributi=
on of the fund is more different from that of its benchmark, which, in turn=
, indicates increased use of ESG information by the fund manager when makin=
g active portfolio decisions. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If there is complex, material ESG information =
that cannot be captured by an ESG rating alone, then analyzing ESG informat=
ion effectively should require specialization. We would, plausibly, expect =
that ESG funds are more likely to have managers with particular expertise i=
n ESG information, and thus we would also expect that the impact on perform=
ance of increased Active ESG Share will be larger among ESG funds.=C2=A0</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Just like regular investment funds can either =
be actively managed or =E2=80=9Ccloset indexers=E2=80=9D who mostly track t=
he index, ESG funds can either have active idiosyncratic views about what c=
ompanies are good for ESG, or can just track published benchmarks. If you j=
ust track the benchmarks then you will, in a certain light, have better ESG=
 performance, because=C2=A0<em>the benchmarks are the ESG performance</em>.=
 But that might not be quite what one wants in an ESG manager.</p>
