<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbu=
siness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvYzVlMT=
E4ZTktODEyNS00OGU1LThlOTAtODc5OTM5ODM3ZDNh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa69dc18=
a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> here you go</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Liquidity is no longer the biggest worry for t=
raders in financial markets, following a year in which markets survived a s=
eries of major shocks without the ability to buy and sell becoming too seve=
rely impaired.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, volatility has climbed to the top of =
the list of traders=E2=80=99 concerns in 2023, as rising global interest ra=
tes and geopolitical tensions spark big moves in markets, according to a su=
rvey of traders by JPMorgan.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders and investors had for the previous six=
 years listed liquidity as their biggest concern, with many worrying about =
the risk of a financial accident caused by a breakdown in the functioning o=
f important markets, including in US Treasuries that form the bedrock of gl=
obal finance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Scott Wacker, head of fixed income, curren=
cy and commodity ecommerce sales at JPMorgan said that in 2022 =E2=80=9Cwe =
didn=E2=80=99t see many breaks in the system in terms of liquidity=E2=80=9D=
, despite market shocks including the fallout from Russia=E2=80=99s invasio=
n of Ukraine and the crisis that hit UK pension funds and the gilt market.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe underlying availability of liquid=
ity was there and the markets functioned really well,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could have a model that is like =E2=80=9Cw=
hen markets are calm and nothing is happening, people worry that if things=
=C2=A0<em>do </em>happen they won=E2=80=99t be able to sell their stuff, bu=
t when things are happening regularly, people are more worried about the th=
ings that are happening than they are about their hypothetical ability to s=
ell stuff.=E2=80=9D When liquidity is good and there are no crises, it is e=
asy to say =E2=80=94=C2=A0and hard to disprove =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwell=
 if there=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>a crisis, liquidity would be bad.=E2=80=9D=
 But once you have enough crises and liquidity keeps being fine, you have t=
o stop saying that.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, I mean, one could quibble. Russia invade=
d Ukraine and, as an indirect result, the London Metal=C2=A0Exchange=C2=A0<=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30425143.266450/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTEtMzAvbWF0dC=
1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1uaWNrZWwtbWFya2V0LWFsbW9zdC1icm9rZT9jbXBpZD1CQ=
kQwMjAxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRl=
ciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAyMDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB642dd720" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"><em>shut down nickel trading for a week</em></a>. N=
ot very good liquidity, in nickel, that week. But when you=E2=80=99re surve=
yed at the end of the year, you might not remember that as a=C2=A0<em>liqui=
dity problem</em>; you might remember that as an extreme instance of market=
 volatility. =E2=80=9CLiquidity=E2=80=9D is sort of an abstract structural=
=C2=A0thing to worry about when you don=E2=80=99t have any immediate worrie=
s; when you have the immediate worries, you tend not to think of them as =
=E2=80=9Cliquidity.=E2=80=9D</p>
